<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSIC REVIEWS; HOLZMAIR LIVES UP TO BILLING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS PASLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Before his Los Angeles debut Monday at the University Synagogue in Brentwood, 
Austrian baritone Wolfgang Holzmair had been heralded as a major talent in San 
Francisco, where he sang in the Brahms Requiem in September, and in his U.S. 
debut in a New York recital at the Frick Museum last January. 
</P>
<P>
 The tall, handsome Austrian, who is in his early 40s, amply confirmed that 
impression in offering a youthful and virile -- and uninterrupted -- 
interpretation of Schubert's "Die Schone Mullerin." 
</P>
<P>
 The voice showed strength, vibrancy, flexibility and focus. There was evenness 
of warm tone throughout the range and at all dynamic levels, and while it was 
not always deeply nuanced, his interpretation of character and text usually 
proved intelligent. 
</P>
<P>
 The progress from exuberant youthfulness to final catastrophe was carefully 
calibrated, although Holzmair may have misjudged his own power in his harsh, 
vigorous projection of jealousy and anger in "Der Jager" and "Eifersucht und 
Stolz." 
</P>
<P>
 But his restraint in the ensuing "Trockne Blumen," the lovely, differently 
lighter voices in "Der Muller and der Bach" and the gentle benediction of the 
closing "Des Baches Wiegenlied" made generous amends. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite a muddy-sounding Steinway, pianist Thomas Palm generally provided 
Holzmair with sensitive and supportive accompaniment. CHRIS PASLES 
</P>
</TEXT>
