<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: DEL CAMPO COMMITS TO RUN FOR UCLA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Brandon Del Campo of Thousand Oaks High, the 1993 Southern Section Division I 
champion in cross-country, has made a verbal commitment to attend UCLA. 
</P>
<P>
 "The program that they have there for student-athletes is very complete and I 
like that," Del Campo said. "They're not going to let you slide." 
</P>
<P>
 Del Campo followed his victory in the Southern Section championships with a 
fourth-place finish in the state Division I championships and 13th-place effort 
in the Foot Locker West regional. Basketball  
</P>
<P>
 Canyon High boys' basketball Coach Greg Hayes apparently is delivering on the 
promise he made to his players last week after the Foothill League decided to 
cancel one-third of its league games. Hayes said he would find some nonleague 
games to make up for the four-game loss and here's what he has scheduled: 
</P>
<P>
 * A nonleague game at Foothill League rival Burbank on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 * A nonleague game at home against L.A. Baptist on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 * A nonleague game at league rival Burroughs next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Canyon also plays host to a league game Saturday against Burroughs. 
</P>
<P>
 Saugus and Hart are scheduled to play a Foothill League game Friday at The 
Master's College. Burroughs and Burbank scheduled a nonleague game Feb. 10. 
Girls' Volleyball  
</P>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks High volleyball player Janette Penfield plans to sign a national 
letter of intent today to play for Colorado State. 
</P>
<P>
 Penfield's identical 6-foot-2 twin, Carolyn, orally committed to Arizona last 
week and also plans to sign today. Janette said that being separated from her 
sister will be difficult but was not a factor in their college choices. 
</P>
<P>
 The coaches from each school promised the Penfields they would schedule 
nonconference matches against each other, Janette said. Softball  
</P>
<P>
 The Cal State Northridge softball team received a No. 6 ranking in an NCAA 
Division I preseason poll released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Arizona is ranked No. 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
