<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: THOUSAND OAKS; STUDY ASKED ON NEON SIGNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEPHANIE SIMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Reluctant to impose hastily drafted regulations on local businesses, the 
Thousand Oaks City Council on Tuesday decided to refer the issue of neon signs 
to a committee for further study. 
</P>
<P>
 Several council members indicated their desire to regulate the number and size 
of neon advertising signs, which they said have proliferated over the last 
several years.But they agreed with Councilwoman Jaime Zukowski that a committee 
of citizens, business representatives and city officials should analyze the 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
 Existing city codes contain no mention of neon signs. To date, the glowing 
advertisements have been considered window signs, which do not require permits 
and can be displayed indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
 But, after studying one citizen's exhaustive list of 318 neon advertisements 
on three main roads, council members decided to consider adding new 
restrictions to the city's sign ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm not in favor of a whole lot of business regulation, but we need to have 
some uniformity," Councilwoman Judy Lazar said before the meeting. STEPHANIE 
SIMON 
</P>
</TEXT>
