<HEADLINE>
<P>
AIR PRODUCTS WILL BUILD 6 NEW FACILITIES IN CALIFORNIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOT J. PALTROW, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a move state leaders are expected to tout as a sign of rising confidence in 
California's economy and business climate, Air Products & Chemicals Inc. will 
announce plans today to spend $270 million to build six new plants and expand 
others in the Golden State over the next two years. 
</P>
<P>
 The new plants will be in Orange County, Santa Fe Springs, another location 
near Los Angeles and in Martinez in the Bay Area.Air Products, which makes 
industrial gases, chemicals and environmental systems, will also expand an 
existing facility in City of Industry. 
</P>
<P>
 Details will be announced at a New York news conference this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
 Patrick J. Witmer, state government relations manager for Allentown, Pa.-based 
Air Products, said Tuesday that the new facilities will create about 90 
permanent jobs. But many workers will be employed building the plants, he said, 
and the expansion will increase Air Products' capital investment in California 
by 50%. 
</P>
<P>
 The new facilities will make products designed to help companies reduce air 
pollution, Air Products said. 
</P>
