<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; NEW POLICE CHIEF REORGANIZES FORCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT LAIT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In one of his first official acts, Police Chief Randall Gaston has reorganized 
the Police Department to reduce administrative positions and reallocate 
resources. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to make sure that we are running the department in a lean, 
administrative way," said Gaston, who announced the reorganization on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 As part of the restructuring, the department will eliminate one of five 
captain's positions. The slot eliminated is the one that Gaston vacated after 
he became chief last month. 
</P>
<P>
 Additionally, five police divisions are being renamed, reassigned and 
consolidated into four divisions. The new divisions are: Community Services, 
Detective, Patrol and Special Operations. 
</P>
<P>
 He said the restructuring will save some money, which will then be funneled 
into other police services. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to have less administrative costs and take those savings and apply 
them to existing field operations," Gaston said.MATT LAIT 
</P>
