<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; SCHOOL BOARD VOTES TO ELIMINATE 36 JOBS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trustees for the Orange Unified School District unanimously voted last week to 
eliminate 36 jobs to close a $485,000 shortfall in its $107-million 1993-94 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
 The board's 7-0 vote Thursday night follows a steady course of 
budget-tightening over three years. In that time, the district has slashed 
$11.5 million from budgets, resulting in layoffs to teachers and classified 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
 In January, the board approved cutting expenses for administrators, which 
saved about $180,000. A proposal to trim benefits to trustees is pending. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nobody wishes more than me that layoffs weren't necessary," said Trustee Max 
Reissmueller Thursday night. "Life is life, and we can't pay what we don't 
have." 
</P>
<P>
 The board ignored a plea from the president of the classified employees union 
to postpone a decision on the layoffs until negotiations between the union and 
the district could be concluded. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was surprised the vote was 7 to zip," said union President Becky Mayers. 
"It tells me there are people up there who haven't been laid off before and 
don't know what it feels like." 
</P>
<P>
 The board had delayed a vote on the layoffs in December and hoped that 
scheduled talks between union and district officials could offer cost-trimming 
measures elsewhere. At Thursday night's meeting, Interim Supt. Marilyn Corey 
said the district would lose $90,000 for each month it pushed back 
implementation of the layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 "Each delay could result in deeper cuts in services to students," said Corey, 
who recommended the board approve the layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 After the vote, Mayers was hopeful a plan could be developed that retained the 
jobs by slashing union costs elsewhere. Mayers would not say where the cuts 
would come from. School officials said Thursday if such a plan were devised and 
agreed upon, the union jobs could be retained. 
</P>
<P>
 But Trustee Bob Viviano wasn't quite as optimistic about the prospect of such 
an agreement between the district and the union, who have been engaged in talks 
since the summer. 
</P>
<P>
 "The fact we are going to have a meeting doesn't mean we are going to have an 
agreement," he said. MARTIN MILLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
